  1. Get a frequency breakdown of the number of chicks, their average weight and the standard deviation of the weights in each of the diets at the start of the study. Store the resulting data frame in a variable named weight0 and print.
weight0 <- ChickWeight %>% 
  filter(Time == 0) %>% 
  group_by(Diet) %>% 
  summarise(mean = mean(weight),
            SD = sd(weight, na.rm=TRUE),
            n=n())
weight0
## # A tibble: 4 x 4
##   Diet   mean    SD     n
##   <fct> <dbl> <dbl> <int>
## 1 1      41.4 0.995    20
## 2 2      40.7 1.49     10
## 3 3      40.8 1.03     10
## 4 4      41   1.05     10
weight0 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=Diet,weight=mean, fill=Diet))+geom_bar()+theme_bw()+geom_errorbar( aes(x=Diet, ymin=mean-SD, ymax=mean+SD), width=0.4, colour="orange", alpha=0.9, size=1.3)

  1. Each chick should have twelve weight measurements. Use the dplyr package to identify how many measurements are there for each chick. Extract a subset of the data for all chicks with complete information, name the data set complete, and print the first 3 rows. (Hint: you might want to use mutate to introduce a helper variable consisting of the number of observations)
complete <- ChickWeight %>% 
  group_by(Chick) %>% 
  mutate(total = n()) %>% 
  filter(total == 12)

  1. In the complete data set introduce a new variable that measures the current weight difference compared to day 0. Name this variable weightgain and print the first 3 rows of the new data frame.
complete <- complete %>% 
  group_by(Chick) %>% 
  mutate(weightgain = weight - weight[Time == 0])
head(complete, n=3)
## # A tibble: 3 x 6
## # Groups:   Chick [1]
##   weight  Time Chick Diet  total weightgain
##    <dbl> <dbl> <ord> <fct> <int>      <dbl>
## 1     42     0 1     1        12          0
## 2     51     2 1     1        12          9
## 3     59     4 1     1        12         17
  1. Use {ggplot2} to create side-by-side boxplots of weightgain by Diet for day 21. Change the order of the categories in the Diet variable such that the boxplots are ordered by median weightgain, and the lower limit of the y axis should be 0. Describe the relationship in 2-3 sentences.
complete %>% 
  filter(Time == 21) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=fct_reorder(Diet,weightgain), y=weightgain, fill=Diet))+geom_boxplot()+theme_bw()

With this data, we want to have the weightgain to be as large as possible. So, we want the diets that had the most weight gain. From the boxplot, we can see that diet 3 had the highest average and diet 1 had the lowest average.

  1. Answer each of the following questions using numerical and graphical summary. Also explain what you found: (a) Which chick gained the most weight and which gained the least weight? (b) What diets were they on?
complete %>% 
  filter(Time == 21) %>% 
  ungroup(Chick) %>% 
  mutate(Chick=fct_reorder(Chick, weightgain)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=Chick, y=weightgain))+geom_point()+theme_bw()

Chick 35 gained the most amount of weight and Chick 24 gained the least amount of weight.

  1. Add to the previous plot the average growth trajectory for all chicks (calculated as the mean weight for each chick at each time). How do the trajectories compare?
completeAvg <- complete %>% 
  group_by(Time) %>% 
  mutate(meanweight = mean(weight))

ggplot()+geom_smooth(data = completeleast, aes(x=Time, y=weight),method='lm',se=FALSE)+
  geom_smooth(data = completeAvg, aes(x=Time, y=weight),method='lm',se=FALSE,color='red')+
  geom_smooth(data = completemost, aes(x=Time, y=weight),method='lm',se=FALSE, color='green')+
  theme_bw()

The trajectories compare similarly in that they are all increasing. The chicks that weighed less had a higher trajectory compared to the mean and the chicks that weighed more had a lower trjectory compared to the mean.

  1. What else do you find interesting in the dataset? Show your exploratory analysis.
complete1 <- complete %>% 
  filter(Diet == 1) %>% 
  group_by(Time) %>% 
  mutate(meanweight = mean(weight))
complete2 <- complete %>% 
  filter(Diet == 2) %>% 
  group_by(Time) %>% 
  mutate(meanweight = mean(weight)) 
complete3 <- complete %>% 
  filter(Diet== 3) %>% 
  group_by(Time) %>% 
  mutate(meanweight = mean(weight))
complete4 <- complete %>% 
  filter(Diet == 4) %>% 
  group_by(Time) %>% 
  mutate(meanweight = mean(weight))  

ggplot()+geom_line(data = complete1, aes(x=Time, y=meanweight),color="red")+
  geom_line(data = complete2, aes(x=Time, y=meanweight),color="blue")+
  geom_line(data = complete3, aes(x=Time, y=meanweight),color="green")+
  geom_line(data = complete4, aes(x=Time, y=meanweight),color="yellow")+theme_bw()

I was interested in the change in mean weight between all of the diets. I first created 4 separate datasets each based on a specific diet. From above, we can see that diet 1 and 2 were similar in growth over time. But we can see that diet 4 was the best for over 50% of the time until about time 14 where diet 3 was better.
